> In C, this is easy! It can be done quickly and cleanly by adding some global variables. In purely functional code, this is somewhere between a major rearchitecting of the data flow and hopeless.<p>&quot;Cleanly&quot; and &quot;global variables&quot; never mesh.<p>> Here&#x27;s a simple statement:<p><pre><code>    if (a > 0) {
        a++;
    }
</code></pre>
> In single-assignment form a new variable is introduced to avoid modifying an existing variable, and the result is rather Erlangy:<p><pre><code>    if (a > 0) {
       a1 = a + 1;
    } else {
       a1 = a;
    }

</code></pre>
Er. Plenty of functional languages will let you shadow existing bindings:<p><pre><code>    let a = if a > 0 then a+1 else a
</code></pre>
However, if you held a reference to &#x27;a&#x27; before the shadowing, its value will not change.
